<HEADLINE>
<P>
INSURANCE COMMISSIONER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Your endorsement of Republican Bannister is an endorsement for more Sacramento 
gridlock. Whoever is elected must go to the Legislature for laws that will put 
his policies into effect. 
</P>
<P>
The October issue of the California Journal lists 16 of the 20 Senate and 42 
Assembly seats as "safe Democratic" in the November election. If the GOP wins 
all the other seats (unlikely), the state Legislature will still be controlled 
by Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
Some of your past editorials have deplored the effects of the Deukmejian-Honig 
feud on California education. Why promote another? 
</P>
<P>
The only sensible vote in 1990 is to vote a straight Democratic ticket. That 
way if the Democrats don't produce before 1994, "Throw the rascals out" will be 
a real option for California voters. If every incumbent was turned out this 
election, the gridlock mix would still be in place, only the party affiliations 
would be changed. 
</P>
<P>
ERNEST HANNA, Long Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
