<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROOF CAVES IN, BURNING 2 FIREFIGHTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two Los Angeles County firefighters received first- and second-degree burns 
when the roof fell in as they battled a blaze that destroyed a house in Santa 
Clarita early Sunday, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
Capt. Joe Romero received second-degree burns when the falling debris knocked 
off his air mask and dropped hot embers under a protective hood covering his 
neck, Capt. Dennis Adkins said. 
</P>
<P>
Romero and firefighter John Hannah, who also was burned on the neck, were 
treated at Henry Mayo Newhall Memorial Hospital and released. 
</P>
<P>
No one was in the house in the 27000 block of Pine Hills Avenue when the fire 
broke out about 12:12 a.m. The cause was under investigation. Damage to the 
house and contents was estimated at $350,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA102990-0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 299711 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 29, 1990, Monday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 16; Column 2; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
259 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
University of San Diego (14-2-5, 1-2-1) got a score from Paul Gelvezon in 
regulation and one from Vince Bianchi in overtime for a 2-2 West Coast 
Conference tie with visiting St. Mary's College (9-8-3, 2-1-1). Toby Taitano, 
Lee Ronces and Philip Burton each had assists for USD. 
</P>
<P>
Curtis McAlister recorded his eighth shutout and host San Diego State beat 
Santa Clara, 1-0, in a nonconference match. SDSU's Brian Craft-Negrete scored 
in the 61st minute off an assist from Jeff Wale. SDSU is 11-6-2. Santa Clara, 
ranked No. 1 in the nation earlier in the year, is 11-3-3. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
BIATHLON 
</P>
<P>
Brent Steiner of Tempe, Ariz., won his fifth race in the 1990 Coors Light 
Biathlon Series, covering the San Diego course in 1 hour 7 minutes 42 seconds. 
The lower times were due to a shorter bike course than the standard 30 
kilometers. This was the final race before the series championship Nov. 11 in 
Phoenix. Joel Thompson of Encinitas was third in 1:09.44 and Oceanside's John 
Groulx was fourth in 1:09.59. 
</P>
<P>
Sally Grand of Plymouth, N.H., won the women's race in 1:18:05. Leucadia's 
Colleen Gallagher finished sixth in 1:22.55 and Del Mar's Nancy Thomas was 
ninth in 1:24.41. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
BOAT RACING 
</P>
<P>
Anaheim's Gordon Jennings, Jr. scored 800 points in his superstocks flat-bottom 
runabout to win the 16th Gordon Jennings Memorial Regatta off Mission Bay. 
Jennings defeated Mike Anderson by 200 points. Among the other winners was San 
Diego's Jon Church, who won the formula cobra/inboard hydroplane race, 
defeating El Cajon's Scott Del Nero and Kevin Aylesworth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA102990-0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 299712 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 29, 1990, Monday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 15A; Column 2; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
246 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHARGER REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
REPORT CARD / T.J. SIMERS; 
</P>
<P>
NOTHING AVERAGE ABOUT THESE MARKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By T.J. SIMERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
B+ QUARTERBACKS 
</P>
<P>
All those who booed Billy Joe Tolliver may apologize by contacting Stella, the 
Chargers' receptionist, at 280-2111. No collect calls, please. 
</P>
<P>
B RUNNING BACKS 
</P>
<P>
Tolliver on Marion Butts: "He'll give you religion in a hurry if you're trying 
to tackle him." Amen. Rod Bernstine brings Bucs to their knees. 
</P>
<P>
C- RECEIVERS 
</P>
<P>
Instead of dressing as a ghost for Halloween, youngsters may want to go as 
Charger wide receivers. Same difference. Only Anthony Miller stands out. 
</P>
<P>
B- OFFENSIVE LINE 
</P>
<P>
Who are these guys? No sacks. Four rushing touchdowns. What's next? It's like 
waking up to discover Rosanne Barr has been selected Miss America. 
</P>
<P>
A DEFENSIVE LINE 
</P>
<P>
Lee Williams drops Howard Hughes imitation and breaks out of hiding to get 
first solo sack since Cleveland. Burt Grossman has 17 sacks in last 17 games. 
</P>
<P>
A LINEBACKERS 
</P>
<P>
Asking Gary (the plowhorse) Plummer to cover Gary Anderson is like asking 
Buster Douglas not to eat. Fat chance, but then check out the final stats. 
</P>
<P>
B- DEFENSIVE BACKS 
</P>
<P>
All-out blitz backfires, but stats have Chargers tied for NFL lead with 14 
interceptions. After the Reds swept the A's, you knew anything was possible. 
</P>
<P>
A SPECIAL TEAMS 
</P>
<P>
Chargers make mulligan count in re-signing John (never a doubt) Carney. Kickoff 
unit limits Bucs to average return of 10.8 yards a try. Why bother? 
</P>
<P>
A COACHING 
</P>
<P>
All those who were asking for Dan Henning's firing may apologize by contacting 
Stella, the Chargers' receptionist, at 280-2111. 
</P>
</TEXT>
